The following abstract is from the article "Pharmacological evaluation of the ethanolic extract of Sutherlandia frutescens for anti-inflammatory activity in vitro and in vivo" by Thabethe, D.A.

Abstract:
Sutherlandia frutescens (L.) R. Br. is a medicinal plant used in traditional South African herbal medicine for the treatment of various diseases, including inflammatory conditions. This study investigated the anti-inflammatory activity of the ethanolic extract of S. frutescens (ESf) using in vitro and in vivo models. The 50% ethanolic extract of S. frutescens was prepared and subjected to phytochemical screening. The extract was then evaluated for its anti-inflammatory activity using the nitric oxide (NO) production inhibition assay, lipopolysaccharide (LPS)-induced paw edema model, and carrageenan-induced paw edema model. The results showed that ESf significantly (p < 0.05) inhibited NO production in RAW 264.7 macrophages stimulated with lipopolysaccharide (LPS). In the LPS-induced paw edema model, ESf significantly (p < 0.05) reduced paw edema volume. In the carrageenan-induced paw edema model, ESf significantly (p < 0.05) reduced paw edema volume and increased plethysmographic pressure. These findings suggest that ESf possesses significant anti-inflammatory activity.

