{"DRUG": ["Sodium-glucose cotransporter 2 inhibitors"]}

SGLT2 inhibitors are a class of antidiabetic drugs that work by inhibiting the sodium-glucose cotransporter 2 in the proximal tubules of the kidney, leading to increased urinary glucose excretion and reduced reabsorption of glucose by the kidneys. Examples of SGLT2 inhibitors include canagliflozin, dapagliflozin, and empagliflozin.

